Indicating relationship between weather and departure delays

fws<- ggplot(weather_join,
             aes(x=visib, y=dep_delay))

fws + geom_point(aes(alpha = 0.01, colour = humid, size = canceled))
## Warning: Removed 9201 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Here we find that visbility increases the occurence of departure delays. There also seems to be a stronger correlation with low humidity and delays over high humidity and delays

Indicating relationship between hour and departure delays, Max delays and Avg delays

This plot shows that early morning hours typically experience a delay, ranging from 200 to 400 minutes if we reference the average (blue dashed line). After about the 5th or 6th hour of the day, average delays remain very low, increasing ever so slightly as the day goes on. The extreme flight delays typically occur between the 6th and 12th hours of the day.

Indicating relationship between days and departure delays, Max Delays

This plot only shows max delays for days throughout the given month. There is typically a spike in delays with in the 8 to 10 day mark, and then max delays typically die down as the month goes by.

Indicating relationship between days and delays, Avg Delays

This represents average delays on a given day and shows very similar behavior to max delays

Indicating relationship between Time of Year and delay, Max Delays

From this we can interpret that there is no significant trend in max delays during a given year.

Indicating relationship between Time of Year and delay, Avg Delays

The same can be concluded for average delays

Here I’ve run a regression of flights cancelled on destinations. All destinations appear to have a positive but very insignificant relationship with cancellations. We can interpret that destinations will not really determine whether there is a cancellation.

Indicating relationship between plane characteristics and Delays

From this we can interpret that the Fixed wing multi engine leads to the most delays compared to the fixed wing singe engine and the Rotorcraft.

Indicating relationship between plane characteristics and Cancellations

Blue dots are indicated by a flight being cancelled and black dots are indicated by flights not being cancelled. From here we can see that a flight is more likely to be cancelled if it has fewer seats and is a turbo-jet plane or a turbo-fan plane.
